@title Catalyst: The Multi-Chain Swap pool
 @author Catalyst Labs
 @notice Catalyst multi-chain swap pool using the asset specific
 pricing curve: W/(w · ln(2)) where W is an asset specific
 weight and w is the pool balance.
 The following contract supports between 1 and 3 assets for
 atomic swaps. To increase the number of tokens supported,
 change NUMASSETS to the desired maximum token amount.
 Implements the ERC20 specification, such that the contract
 will be its own pool token.
 @dev This contract is deployed /broken/: It cannot be used as a
 swap pool as is. To use it, a proxy contract duplicating the
 logic of this contract needs to be deployed. In vyper, this
 can be done through (vy 0.3.4) create_minimal_proxy_to.
 After deployment of the proxy, call setup(...). This will
 initialize the pool and prepare it for cross-chain transactions.
 If connected to a supported cross-chain interface, call
 createConnection or createConnectionWithChain to connect the
 pool with pools on other chains.
 Finally, call finishSetup to give up the deployer's control
 over the pool.

@notice Setup a pool.
 @dev The @param amp is only used as a sanity check and needs to be set to 2**64.
 If less than NUMASSETS are used to setup the pool, let the remaining init_assets be ZERO_ADDRESS
 The unused weights can be whatever. (however, 0 is recommended.)
 The initial token amounts should have been sent to the pool before setup.
 If any token has token amount 0, the pool will never be able to have more than
 0 tokens for that token.

natspec.details: This contract is deployed /broken/: It cannot be used as a swap pool as is. To use it, a proxy contract duplicating the logic of this contract needs to be deployed. In vyper, this can be done through (vy 0.3.4) create_minimal_proxy_to. After deployment of the proxy, call setup(...). This will initialize the pool and prepare it for cross-chain transactions. If connected to a supported cross-chain interface, call createConnection or createConnectionWithChain to connect the pool with pools on other chains. Finally, call finishSetup to give up the deployer's control over the pool.

LocalSwap(address,address,address,uint25.notice: Describes an atomic swap between the 2 tokens: _fromAsset and _toAsset.

SwapFromUnits(address,address,uint256,ui.notice: Describes the arrival of an external swap: Cross-chain swap.

SwapToUnits(bytes32,bytes32,address,uint.notice: Describes the creation of an external swap: Cross-chain swap.

_max_unit_inflow().notice: The max incoming liquidity flow from the router.

_onlyLocal().notice: If the pool has no cross chain connection, this is true.     Should not be trusted if setupMaster != ZERO_ADDRESS

_setupMaster().notice: The setupMaster is the short-term owner of the pool.     They can connect the pool to pools on other chains.

_tokenIndexing(uint256).notice: To indicate which token is desired on the target pool,     the _toAsset is an integer from 0 to NUMASSETS indicating     which asset the pool should purchase with units.

_weight(address).notice: The token weights. Used for maintaining a non symmetric pool balance.

approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. NOTE: If `amount` is the maximum `uint256`, the allowance is not updated on `transferFrom`. This is semantically equivalent to an infinite approval. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

approx_solve_integral(uint256,uint256,ui.details: This function should sometimes be used over _solve_integral. Since the error is relative to _out and _B, it is difficult to provide relative bounds when the approximation is better than the true equation. All input amounts should be the raw numbers and not X64. Since units are always denominated in X64, the function should be treated as mathematically *native*.
approx_solve_integral(uint256,uint256,ui.notice: Solves the equation U = \int_{B-_out}^{B} W/(w · ln(2)) dw for _out by upper approximation. After swapping, we know the price to be W/((B - out) · ln(2)). The amount provided to the seller is then (W · _out)/((A - _out) · ln(2)).     => _out = (B · U · LN2)/(W + U · LN2)

params.B: The current pool balance of the _out token.
params.U: Input units. Is technically X64 but can be treated as not.
params.W: The pool weight of the _out token.

createConnection(bytes32,bytes32,bool).details: if _poolReceiving is an EVM pool, it can be computes as:     Vyper: convert(_poolAddress, bytes32)     Solidity: abi.encode(_poolAddress)     Brownie: brownie.convert.to_bytes(_poolAddress, type_str="bytes32") ! Notice, using tx.origin is not secure. However, it makes it easy to bundle call from an external contract and no assets are at risk because the pool should not be used without setupMaster == ZERO_ADDRESS
createConnection(bytes32,bytes32,bool).notice: Creates a connection to the pool _poolReceiving on the channel _channelId.

params.poolReceiving: The bytes32 representation of the target pool
params.state: # todo: Should we also set this to True? Aka: should we disable disabling a connection?

Using tx.origin is not secure. However, it makes it easy to bundle call from an external contract and no assets are at risk because the pool should not be used without setupMaster == ZERO_ADDRESS
createConnectionWithChain(uint256,bytes3.notice: Creates a connection to the pool _poolReceiving using the lookup table of the interface.

params.chainId: _chainId of the target pool. The interface will convert the chainId to the correct channelId.
params.poolReceiving: The bytes32 representation of the target pool
params.state: # todo: Should we also set this to True? Aka: should we disable disabling a connection?

decimals().details: Returns the number of decimals used to get its user representation. For example, if `decimals` equals `2`, a balance of `505` tokens should be displayed to a user as `5.05` (`505 / 10 ** 2`). Tokens usually opt for a value of 18, imitating the relationship between Ether and Wei. This is the value {ERC20} uses, unless this function is overridden; NOTE: This information is only used for _display_ purposes: it in no way affects any of the arithmetic of the contract, including {IERC20-balanceOf} and {IERC20-transfer}.

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

depositAll(uint256).details: Requires approvals for all tokens within the pool.
depositAll(uint256).notice: Deposits a symmetrical number of tokens such that baseAmount of pool tokens are minted. This doesn't change the pool price.

params.baseAmount: The number of pool tokens to mint.

dry_liquidity_from_unit(address,uint256,.notice: Computes the output of a liquidity swap from units into liquidity, without executing one.

params.U: The number of units used to buy liquidity of to.
params.WSUM: The weighted sum used to solve the liquidity constraints. TODO: Approx?
params.to: The token address of the target balance0.

dry_liquidity_to_unit(address,uint256).notice: Computes the return of a liquidity swap from liquidity into units, without executing one.

params.amount: The amount of _from liquidity to sell. TODO: Approx?
params.from: The address of the liquidity to sell.

returns._0: Liquidity units in X64 (units are **always** X64).

dry_swap_both(address,address,uint256,bo.details: If the pool weights of the 2 tokens are equal, a very simple curve is used and argument approx is ignored. Before letting a user swap, it can be beneficial to viewing the approximated and not approximated. Then choose the one with the lowest cost (max return & min gas cost). If the pool weights of the 2 tokens are equal, a very simple curve is used and argument approx is ignored..
dry_swap_both(address,address,uint256,bo.notice: Computes the return of a SwapToAndFromUnits, without executing one.

params.approx: True if SwapToUnits should be approximated (read: approx_compute_integral) Is ignored if the tokens weights are equal.
params.from: The address of the token to sell.
params.input: The amount of _from token to sell for to token.
params.to: The address of the token to buy.

dry_swap_from_unit(address,uint256,bool).details: Before letting a user swap, it can be beneficial to viewing the return approximated and not approximated. Then choose the one with the lowest cost (max return & min gas cost).
dry_swap_from_unit(address,uint256,bool).notice: Computes the output of a SwapFromUnits, without executing one.

params.U: The number of units used to buy to.
params.approx: True if SwapToUnits should be approximated (read: _approx_solve_integral)
params.to: The address of the token to buy.

dry_swap_to_unit(address,uint256,bool).details: Before letting a user swap, it can be beneficial to viewing the return approximated and not approximated. Then choose the one with the lowest cost (max return & min gas cost).
dry_swap_to_unit(address,uint256,bool).notice: Computes the return of a SwapToUnits, without executing one.

params.amount: The amount of from token to sell.
params.approx: True if SwapToUnits should be approximated (read: approx_compute_integral)
params.from: The address of the token to sell.

returns._0: uint256 specific units in X64 (units are **always** X64).

finishSetup().details: ! Using tx.origin is not secure. However, it makes it easy to bundle call from an external contract and no assets are at risk because the pool should not be used without setupMaster == ZERO_ADDRESS
finishSetup().notice: Gives up short term ownership of the pool. This makes the pool unstoppable.

getLiquidityUnitCapacity().notice: Returns the current cross-chain liquidity unit capacity in terms of the totalSupply. These are not true units but rather the conversion of units to pool tokens.

getUnitCapacity().notice: Returns the current cross-chain unit capacity.

inLiquidity(address,uint256).details: Can only be called by the chaininterface, as there is no way to check the validity of units.
inLiquidity(address,uint256).notice: Completes a cross-chain swap by converting liquidity units to pool tokens Called exclusively by the chaininterface.

params.U: Number of units to convert into pool tokens.

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

localswap(address,address,uint256,uint25.notice: A swap between 2 assets which both are inside the pool. Is atomic.

params.amount: The amount of fromAsset the user wants to sell
params.fromAsset: The asset the user wants to sell.
params.minOut: The minimum output of _toAsset the user wants.
params.toAsset: The asset the user wants to buy

localswap(address,address,uint256,uint25.notice: A swap between 2 assets which both are inside the pool. Is atomic.

params.amount: The amount of fromAsset the user wants to sell
params.approx: If true, uses (worse) but simpler swapping which can improve swap return and gas costs. If assets weights are equal, this is ignored.
params.fromAsset: The asset the user wants to sell.
params.minOut: The minimum output of _toAsset the user wants.
params.toAsset: The asset the user wants to buy

name().details: Returns the name of the token.

outLiquidity(uint256,bytes32,bytes32,uin.notice: Initiate a cross-chain liquidity swap by lowering liquidity and transfer the liquidity units to another pool.

params.baseAmount: The number of pool tokens to liquidity Swap
params.chain: The target chain. Will be converted by the interface to channelId.
params.targetPool: The target pool on the target chain encoded in bytes32. For EVM chains this can be computed as: Vyper: convert(_poolAddress, bytes32) Solidity: abi.encode(_poolAddress) Brownie: brownie.convert.to_bytes(_poolAddress, type_str="bytes32")
params.targetUser: The recipient of the transaction on _chain. Encoded in bytes32. For EVM chains it can be found similarly to _targetPool.

ready().details: Just checks if the setup master has been set to ZERO_ADDRESS.     In other words, has finishSetup been called?
ready().notice: External view function purely used to signal if a pool is safe to use.

releaseEscrowACK(uint256).notice: Release the escrowed tokens into the pool.

releaseEscrowTIMEOUT(uint256).notice: Returned the escrowed tokens to the user

setup(address,address[],uint256[],uint25.details: The @param amp is only used as a sanity check and needs to be set to 2**64. If less than NUMASSETS are used to setup the pool, let the remaining init_assets be ZERO_ADDRESS The unused weights can be whatever. (however, 0 is recommended.) The initial token amounts should have been sent to the pool before setup. If any token has token amount 0, the pool will never be able to have more than 0 tokens for that token.

swapFromUnits(uint256,address,uint256,ui.details: Can only be called by the chaininterface, as there is no way to check the validity of units.
swapFromUnits(uint256,address,uint256,ui.notice: Completes a cross-chain swap by converting units to the desired token (toAsset)  Called exclusively by the chaininterface.

params.U: Number of units to convert into toAsset.
params.approx: If the swap approximation should be used over the "true" swap.
params.minOut: Minimum number of tokens bought. Reverts if less.
params.toAssetIndex: Index of the asset to be purchased with _U units.

swapToUnits(uint32,bytes32,bytes32,addre.details: Use the appropriate dry swaps to decide if approximation makes sense. These are the same functions as used by the swap functions, so they will accurately predict the gas cost and swap return.
swapToUnits(uint32,bytes32,bytes32,addre.notice: Initiate a cross-chain swap by purchasing units and transfer them to another pool.

params.amount: The number of _fromAsset to sell to the pool.
params.approx: Should SwapFromUnits be computed using approximation?
params.chain: The target chain. Will be converted by the interface to channelId.
params.fallbackUser: If the transaction fails send the escrowed funds to this address
params.fromAsset: The asset the user wants to sell.
params.minOut: The minimum number of returned tokens to the targetUser on the target chain.
params.targetPool: The target pool on the target chain encoded in bytes32. For EVM chains this can be computed as: Vyper: convert(_poolAddress, bytes32) Solidity: abi.encode(_poolAddress) Brownie: brownie.convert.to_bytes(_poolAddress, type_str="bytes32")
params.targetUser: The recipient of the transaction on _chain. Encoded in bytes32. For EVM chains it can be derived similarly to targetPool.
params.toAssetIndex: The index of the asset the user wants to buy in the target pool.

symbol().details: Returns the symbol of the token, usually a shorter version of the name.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `to` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}. NOTE: Does not update the allowance if the current allowance is the maximum `uint256`. Requirements: - `from` and `to` cannot be the zero address. - `from` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``from``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

withdrawAll(uint256).notice: Burns baseAmount and releases the symmetrical share of tokens to the burner. This doesn't change the pool price.

params.baseAmount: The number of pool tokens to burn.
